      <h2>Ranking Methodology</h2>
      <p>Navigating the Indian penny stock market requires extreme caution due to issues related to liquidity and corporate governance. Our methodology is designed to filter out fundamentally flawed companies and highlight those with genuine potential:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Strict Price Threshold:</strong> All companies evaluated must be actively trading below ₹100 on either the NSE or BSE.</li>
        <li><strong>Volume and Liquidity:</strong> We heavily penalize or exclude stocks with extremely low daily trading volumes to ensure investors can enter and exit positions without excessive slippage.</li>
        <li><strong>Promoter Holding and Pledging:</strong> High promoter (founder/management) ownership is viewed favorably as it aligns interests. Conversely, high levels of pledged promoter shares serve as a massive red flag.</li>
        <li><strong>Debt Restructuring Progress:</strong> For companies emerging from distress, we closely monitor their progress in resolving non-performing assets or restructuring existing debt facilities.</li>
        <li><strong>Government Policy Alignment:</strong> Extra weight is given to companies operating in sectors actively supported by current government initiatives, such as 'Make in India' or the PLI (Production Linked Incentive) schemes.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>This rigorous framework attempts to balance the inherent risks of sub-₹100 equities with the potential for massive macroeconomic tailwinds.</p>
